What is a â€œcutâ€? Although many theorems are named after peopleâ€™s names, â€œcutâ€ is not one of them. To understand the â€œcut propertyâ€, we need to understand two basic concepts.

First, in Graph theory, a â€œcutâ€ is a partition of vertices in a â€œgraphâ€ into two disjoint subsets. Figure 11 illustrates a â€œcutâ€, where (B, A, E) forms one subset, and (C, D) forms the other subset.
Second, a crossing edge is an edge that connects a vertex in one set with a vertex in the other set. In Figure 11, (B, C), (A, C), (A, D), (E, D) are all â€œcrossing edgesâ€.

Figure 11. Graph with a cut

After knowing the basics of a graph cut, letâ€™s delve into the â€œcut propertyâ€. The cut property provides theoretical support for Kruskalâ€™s algorithm and Primâ€™s algorithm. So, what is the â€œcut propertyâ€? According to Wikipedia, the â€œcut propertyâ€ refers to:

For any cut C of the graph, if the weight of an edge E in the cut-set of C is strictly smaller than the weights of all other edges of the cut-set of C, then this edge belongs to all MSTs of the graph.



